   Intelligence (CSCI), Las Vegas, NV, DEC 15-17, 2021},
Organization = {Amer Council Sci \& Educ},
Abstract = {There has been an increasing concern that African American community has
   been disproportionately impacted during the coronavirus pandemic. This
   paper analyzes why the African American community is disproportionately
   impacted during the coronavirus pandemic and compares the COVID-19 data
   with hospitalizations, real estate, school closings, and crime data.
   Human behavior was impacted as a result of lockdown due to COVID
   pandemic and it lead to a shift in crime dynamics. We analyze shifts in
   crime types by comparing crimes before and after the COVID pandemic in
   Baltimore. There was a significant decline in total crimes during the
   time period immediately following stay at home orders. Findings show
   that the disproportionality among the African American community is
   significantly influenced by factors such as living in more crowded
   housing situations, working in consumer-facing serviced industries,
   having higher rates of preexisting medical conditions, and lack of
   insurance or a consistent care source.},
